Q1 (a) What is Cryptography? What is its Role in Blockchain? (15 Marks)
Introduction

Cryptography is the science of protecting information by converting it into a secure and unreadable format so that only authorized users can access it.

It uses mathematical techniques such as:

Encryption
Decryption
Hashing
Digital Signatures

Cryptography is the foundation of blockchain security.

Objectives of Cryptography

Cryptography ensures:

Confidentiality – Only authorized users can read data
Integrity – Data is not changed
Authentication – Verifies identity
Non-repudiation – Sender cannot deny transaction
Role of Cryptography in Blockchain
1. Hashing

Each block contains a unique cryptographic hash.

If data changes, the hash also changes
Detects tampering
2. Digital Signatures

Used to verify the identity of users.

Only owner can authorize transaction
Prevents fraud
3. Linking of Blocks

Each block stores the hash of the previous block.

Creates secure chain
Maintains immutability
4. Security and Trust

Cryptography prevents unauthorized changes and builds trust in decentralized systems.

Conclusion

Cryptography plays a vital role in blockchain by ensuring security, integrity, authentication, and trust.

Q1 (b) What Do You Mean by Blocks in Blockchain Technology?
Definition

A block is a data structure that stores a group of transactions in a blockchain network.

Blockchain is made of many blocks connected together in sequence.

Components of a Block

A block contains:

Transaction data
Timestamp
Hash of previous block
Current block hash
Nonce
Role of Blocks
1. Store Transactions

Each block records transaction details.

2. Maintain Order

Transactions are stored in chronological order.

3. Secure Linking

Each block links to previous block using hash.

4. Immutability

Once added, block cannot be changed easily.

5. Transparency

All network participants can verify transactions.

Example

Block 1 → Block 2 → Block 3

If Block 1 changes, all next blocks become invalid.

Conclusion

Blocks are the basic units of blockchain that securely store and connect transaction records.

Q1 (c) What is a Smart Contract? List Some of Its Applications
Definition

A smart contract is a self-executing digital program stored on a blockchain that automatically performs actions when predefined conditions are met.

It works without middlemen.

Features of Smart Contracts
Automatic execution
Transparent
Secure
Fast
Cost-effective
Working Example

If payment is received, product ownership is transferred automatically.

Applications of Smart Contracts
1. Financial Services
Automatic payments
Loan processing
Insurance settlement
2. Decentralized Finance (DeFi)
Lending platforms
Token exchanges
3. Supply Chain Management
Product tracking
Payment after delivery
4. Digital Identity
Identity verification
Access systems
5. Voting Systems
Transparent elections
Tamper-proof voting
6. NFTs and Digital Assets
Ownership transfer
Royalty payments
Conclusion

Smart contracts improve speed, security, transparency, and reduce costs in many industries.

Q2. Explain the Case Study on FinTech in Singapore (15 Marks)
Introduction

Singapore is one of the world’s leading FinTech hubs. It has successfully combined finance, technology, cybersecurity, and strong regulations to create a safe and innovative digital financial ecosystem.

The Monetary Authority of Singapore (MAS) plays a major role in this growth.

Background

Singapore was already a strong financial center with global banks and stable governance.

When digital technology transformed finance, Singapore quickly adopted FinTech to remain globally competitive.

Role of Government and MAS

MAS supports FinTech growth by:

Providing clear regulations
Offering regulatory sandboxes
Giving grants and funding
Encouraging innovation
Ensuring cybersecurity and risk management

This balances innovation with customer protection.

FinTech Ecosystem in Singapore

It includes:

FinTech startups
Banks
Technology companies
Cybersecurity firms
Universities
Investors

Events like Singapore FinTech Festival increase collaboration.

Major FinTech Areas
1. Digital Payments
PayNow
Mobile wallets
QR payments
2. Digital Banking
App-based banking
Digital-only banks
3. Blockchain and Digital Assets
Smart contracts
Secure transactions
Cross-border payments
4. WealthTech and InsurTech
Online investments
Digital insurance services
Cybersecurity Focus

Singapore gives high importance to cybersecurity through:

Strong data protection laws
Cybersecurity Act
Regular audits
Risk management frameworks
Strong authentication systems

This builds trust in digital finance.

Challenges
Rising cyber threats
Data privacy issues
Need for continuous innovation
Global competition
Shortage of skilled professionals
Impact of FinTech in Singapore
Faster financial services
Better customer experience
Increased investment
Strong digital economy
More financial inclusion
Conclusion

Singapore is a successful FinTech model because of strong government support, innovation, security, and collaboration.
